CANONCITE (v0) — LICENSE
========================

This release contains two kinds of material with two different licensing
statuses. Read both sections.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. ANNOTATIONS / QUESTIONS  —  Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The benchmark annotations authored by the CANONCITE project — the questions,
gold_citations, near_miss_distractors, gold_answer, answer_support, question
typing, ambiguity labels, translations, provenance metadata, the manifest, and
the accompanying documentation — are licensed under the

    Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License (CC BY 4.0)
    https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/

You are free to share and adapt this material for any purpose, including
commercially, provided you give appropriate credit, link to the license, and
indicate if changes were made. Attribute as:

    CANONCITE (Shastra / Scripture-RAG), v0. Licensed under CC BY 4.0.

THE MATERIAL IS PROVIDED "AS IS", WITHOUT WARRANTY OF ANY KIND. Gold answers are
textual-attribution judgments, NOT doctrinal or theological rulings for any
tradition.

(Benchmark code — metrics, id grammar, build tooling — is separately available
under the MIT/Apache-2.0 license in the project repository, not covered by this
file.)

================================================================================
                                   NOTICE
================================================================================
2. CORPUS TEXT  —  PUBLIC DOMAIN, PER SOURCE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The scripture and legal text units in `corpora/<corpus>/corpus_index.jsonl` are
NOT owned by the CANONCITE project. Each corpus reproduces text from a
public-domain edition. The underlying canonical texts (Sanskrit / Pali / Tamil /
Gurmukhi scripture, and the Constitution of India) are ancient and/or
government works in the public domain; the specific English translations used
are public-domain editions. Per-record provenance (edition, source URL,
retrieval date) is in each `corpus_index.jsonl`; per-corpus details and sha256
hashes are in each `VALIDATION.md`.

Public-domain editions included in this release:

  * Bhagavad Gita      — Annie Besant, "The Bhagavad-Gita" (4th ed., 1905),
                         public domain. Sanskrit via the gita open dataset
                         (Devanagari + IAST), ancient/public-domain.
  * Bible              — The World English Bible (WEB), public domain.
  * Constitution of    — Government of India public-domain text of the
    India               Constitution.
  * Dhammapada         — F. Max Müller, Sacred Books of the East vol. X (1881),
                         public domain. Pali root text via SuttaCentral
                         (Mahāsaṅgīti), ancient/public-domain.
  * Upanishads         — F. Max Müller, Sacred Books of the East (Upanishads),
                         public domain. Sanskrit via GRETIL, ancient/PD.
  * Yoga Sutras        — Swami Vivekananda / J. H. Woods, Raja-Yoga aphorisms
                         (1896), public domain. Sanskrit via GRETIL, ancient/PD.
  * Ramayana           — Sanskrit (Vālmīki, Baroda Critical Edition) via GRETIL;
                         R. T. H. Griffith English (1870-74) is public domain.
                         RELEASED AS SANSKRIT ONLY (see exclusions).
  * Mahabharata        — Sanskrit via GRETIL; K. M. Ganguli English is public
                         domain. RELEASED AS SANSKRIT ONLY (see exclusions).
  * Thirukkural        — G. U. Pope, "Thirukkural" (1886), public domain.
                         Classical Tamil kural text, ancient/public-domain.
  * Guru Granth Sahib  — Gurmukhi original (public domain) served via
                         GurbaniNow / BaniDB (Shabad OS database, MIT-licensed
                         code; gurbani text public domain).
                         RELEASED AS GURMUKHI ONLY (see exclusions).

Digitization note: some digitizations (e.g. GRETIL) distribute their markup
under CC-BY-NC-SA 4.0 for reference use; the *underlying texts* are ancient and
public-domain. Devanagari originals for some Sanskrit corpora are produced by
deterministic, lossless IAST→Devanagari transliteration of the fetched GRETIL
text (the same text in a second script).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. DELIBERATELY EXCLUDED — COPYRIGHTED / UNALIGNED TRANSLATIONS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The following in-copyright (or non-aligned) English translations are NOT part of
this release and were removed by the build tooling:

  * Guru Granth Sahib  — Dr. Sant Singh Khalsa English translation
                         (copyrighted, US term to ~2096). Excluded; kept private.
  * Ramayana           — IIT-Kanpur English translation (copyrighted). Excluded;
                         kept private. (Griffith PD English could not be aligned
                         to the shloka grid.)
  * Bhagavad Gita      — BBT / Bhaktivedanta (Prabhupada) translation.
                         Not used anywhere in this dataset.
  * Mahabharata        — Ganguli English (public domain) is excluded from the
                         released text layer because it does not align to the
                         critical-edition shloka grid.

The build script `build_release.py` enforces these exclusions: it aborts if any
private/copyrighted artifact, off-allowlist `translation_source`, or English
text in an excluded-English corpus is found.
